#1.1 Write a function
country_list = cases_raw.index.tolist()    #all country in a list
def my_plot(country=country_list,row=len(country_list),data=cases_raw,m=10,n=7):
    for i in range(row):
        plt.subplot(row,1,i+1)
        data.loc[country[i],:].plot(figsize=(m,n))
        plt.xlabel('Date')
        plt.ylabel('Number of Covid cases')
        plt.title(country[i])
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

1.4 Discuss the trends in the standardized time-series for the US, Canada, and China. What does it mean if the curve goes up or down (are the number of covid cases negative?) What does the sign of values indicate?¶

  • If the curve goes up, this means the number of Covid cases was higher in that counrty for that time period if we compare it globally, and vice versa. The trend is not mainly tell us how the epidemic of Covid was changed in the particular country, it is more like indicating the situation compared with other countries, as the case numbers were scaled on each day actully. The number around 0 means the cases in that country was similar with the average cases globally,but we cannot say there was no cases at that time. Similarly, a negative number for a country indicates the Covid was just not as widespread nationally as the average situation.

  • we see the scaled number of Covid cases in China at the begining was very high, but the number in US is around 0, means the case number in US was similar with the global value, and the situation in Canada was better than the other two as it got negative numbers at the beginning. But Covid starts to be spread in Canda and US from March, 2020 as trends goes on. But the people got Covid in Canda on May,2022 was still less than China, meanwhile, there were much more cases in US. After May,2020, the case number in china began to be similar with the gloabl average gradually until the end time of the dataset, and the situation in Canda started to be eased and up a little again, but it was still close to the global average, as the numbers is aroud 0.2. There were more fluctions for US line, but it is clear that the Covid cases was keeping to be higher than other countries.

# 2.2 Write a function that returns sorted eigenvalues and eigenvectors using np.linalg.eigh.
import numpy as np
def get_sorted_eigen(df_cov):
    # Eigen decomposition
    eigenValues, eigenVectors = np.linalg.eigh(df_cov) 
    args = (-eigenValues).argsort()
    eigenValues = eigenValues[args]
    eigenVectors = eigenVectors[:, args]
    return eigenValues,eigenVectors

2.6 Compare the first few PCs with the rest of them. Do you see any difference in their trend?¶

  • We understand the directions of the spread of our data using Eigenvectors. The first several PC are more steady, and the rest of the graphs fluctuate more in both directions and magnitude if we compared with the first few PCs, which means there are more noise as the number of PC increases, like PC14,PC15 or PC16, and it is a bit harder to generalized the overall patterns.

  • Accepts a country and the original dataset as inputs.
  • Calls useful functions that you designed in previous parts to compute eigen vectors and eigen values.

  • Plots 4 figures:

    1. The original time-series for the specified country. [1]

    2. The incremental reconstruction of the original (not standardized) time-series for the specified country in a single plot. [1]

      • You should at least show 5 curves in a figure for incremental reconstruction. For example, you can pick the following (or any other combination that you think is reasonable):

        • Reconstruction with only PC1
        • Reconstruction with both PC1 and PC2
        • Reconstruction with PC1 to PC4 (First 4 PCs)
        • Reconstruction with PC1 to PC8 (First 8 PCs)
        • Reconstruction with PC1 to PC16 (First 16 PCs)

      • Hint: you need to compute the reconstruction for the standardized time-series first, and then scale it back to the original (non-standardized form) using the StandardScaler inverse_transform help...

    3. The residual error for your best reconstruction with respect to the original time-series. [1]
      • Hint: You are plotting the error that we have for reconstructing each day (df - df_reconstructed). On the x-axis, you have dates, and on the y-axis, the residual error.
    4. The RMSE of the reconstruction as a function of the number of included components (x-axis is the number of components and y-axis is the RMSE). Sweep x-axis from 1 to 100 (this part is independent from part 3.2.) [1]

def PCA_plot(country_name):
    for PC_count in [1,2,4,8,16]:
        W = eigenVectors[:, 0:PC_count] 
        projX = np.dot(cases_scaled, W)
        ReconX = np.dot(projX, W.T)
        # scale it back to the original (non-standardized form) using the StandardScaler inverse_transform
        ReconX_original = pd.DataFrame(scaler.inverse_transform(ReconX), columns=cases_raw.columns,index=cases_raw.index)
        ReconX_original.loc[country_name,:].plot(figsize=(10,10),label = 'With the first {} PC(s)'.format(PC_count),title='Reconstruction with PC(s)')
        plt.legend()
    
def error(country_name):
    W = eigenVectors[:, 0:16]   #as more PC==>more variance woule be explained, so choose best amount of PC to be 16
    projX = np.dot(cases_scaled, W)
    ReconX = np.dot(projX, W.T)
    ReconX_original = pd.DataFrame(scaler.inverse_transform(ReconX), columns=cases_raw.columns,index=cases_raw.index)
    (cases_raw.loc[country_name,:]-ReconX_original.loc[country_name,:]).plot(figsize=(10,10),title = 'Residual Error with the first 16 PCs')

from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
def rmse(country_name):  #root mean sqaured error
    rmse=[]
    for i in range(1,101):  #sweep from 1 to 100
        W = eigenVectors[:, 0:i] 
        projX = np.dot(cases_scaled, W)
        ReconX = np.dot(projX, W.T)
        ReconX_original = pd.DataFrame(scaler.inverse_transform(ReconX), columns=cases_raw.columns,index=cases_raw.index)
        rmse.append(mean_squared_error(cases_raw.loc[country_name,:], ReconX_original.loc[country_name,:], squared=False))
    plt.plot(np.arange(1,101),rmse)
    plt.title('RMSE of reconstruction')
    plt.xlabel('Number of Components Included(from 1 to 100)')

Choose 7: "Sneaker",5: "Sandal", 9: "Ankle boot".¶

If we want to reconstruct images better with PCA, we want to compress the ones that are similar that the images are not easily to be seperated, so that we can be more sure to seperate the overall dataset afterward.

#4.2 Compute Eigenvectors and Eigenvalues
def getBasisCountThatPreservesVariance(eigenValues, variance=0.98):
    for idx, cumulativeSum in enumerate(np.cumsum(eigenValues) / np.sum(eigenValues)):
        if cumulativeSum > variance:
            return idx
        
def pca(X, y):
    n, d = X.shape
    mu = X.mean(axis=0)
    X = X - mu # standardising data
    
    if n > d:    #sample>feature, don't used in the new sample with 314 samples actually.
        C = np.dot(X.T,X) / (n-1) # covariance matrix
        eigenValues, eigenVectors = np.linalg.eigh(C)
    else:               #we choose this one, as only 314 samples of shoes.
        C = np.dot(X,X.T) / (n-1) # covariance matrix
        eigenValues, eigenVectors = np.linalg.eigh(C)
        eigenVectors = np.dot(X.T, eigenVectors)
        for i in range(n):
            eigenVectors[:,i] = eigenVectors[:, i] / np.linalg.norm(eigenVectors[:, i])

    print ("Dim of Full Eigen Vectors", eigenVectors.shape)
            
    # sort eigenVectors in descending order by their eigenValue ==> by level of importance
    idx = np.argsort(-eigenValues)
    eigenValues = eigenValues[idx]
    eigenVectors = eigenVectors[:, idx]
    
    # select based on numOfBasis ===> number of PC you need to achive the variance
    numOfBasis = getBasisCountThatPreservesVariance(eigenValues)
    print('Number of useful eigenBasis are: ', numOfBasis)
    eigenValues = eigenValues[0:numOfBasis].copy()
    eigenVectors = eigenVectors[:, 0:numOfBasis].copy()
    return eigenValues, eigenVectors, mu

def project (W , X , mu):
    return np.dot (X - mu , W)
def reconstruct (W , Y , mu) :
    return np.dot (Y , W.T) + mu

    plt.title(COUNT)

4.6 what would be the compression ratio for a dataset with 1000 images?¶

After compression, we store 50 constants for each image. So, the total number of unique values required to store the compressed dataset is 1000 x 50 = 5000 unique values. But, we also need to store the templates to reconstruct the images later. Therefore, we also need to store 50 x 28 x 28 = 39200 unique values for the templates. Therefore, the total number of unique values required to store the compressed dataset is 5000 + 39200 = 44200 unique values.

reference: https://towardsdatascience.com/face-dataset-compression-using-pca-cddf13c63583

In [41]:
print('The compression ratio for a dataset with 1000 images:',(1000* 28* 28-44200)/(1000* 28* 28))
